#MEM id=references source=/root/yvon/agent-department/COO/diana/skills/marketplace/lean-startup/references/applications.md
M|references|The Lean Startup was born in Silicon Valley software startups, but its principles apply wherever there is uncertainty about what to build, who to build it for, or how to build a sustainable business. 
M|references|SaaS is the natural home for lean methodology. Short iteration cycles, measurable user behavior, and flexible dpl make SaaS ideal for rapid experimentation.
M|references|**Phase 1: Problem Validation (Weeks 1-3)**
M|references|- [ ] Identify 30 potential customers in the target segment
M|references|- [ ] Conduct 15-20 problem discovery interviews
M|references|- [ ] Map the current workflow and pain points
M|references|- [ ] Identify the #1 unmet need (the "hair on fire" problem)
M|references|- [ ] Write the value hypothesis
M|references|**Phase 2: Solution Validation (Weeks 4-8)**
M|references|- [ ] Create a landing page describing the solution with pricing
M|references|- [ ] Drive 500+ targeted visitors to measure conversion (target: 3-5% email capture)
M|references|- [ ] Build a concierge or Wizard of Oz MVP for 5-10 engaged prospects
M|references|- [ ] Deliver the service manually; observe behavior and gather feedback
M|references|- [ ] Validate willingness to pay (charge or get letters of intent)
M|references|**Phase 3: Product Build and Iteration (Weeks 9-16)**
M|references|- [ ] Build the single-feature MVP based on concierge learnings
M|references|- [ ] Launch to 20-50 beta users with full instrumentation
M|references|- [ ] Measure activation rate, Day-7 retention, and core feature usage
M|references|- [ ] Run weekly Build-Measure-Learn loops on the biggest engagement gap
M|references|- [ ] Conduct 5 user interviews per week alongside quantitative data
M|references|**Phase 4: Product-Market Fit Assessment (Weeks 17-24)**
M|references|- [ ] Administer Sean Ellis survey ("How would you feel if you could no longer use this product?")
M|references|- [ ] Target: 40%+ respond "very disappointed"
M|references|- [ ] Measure Month-1 retention by cohort (target varies by category)
M|references|- [ ] Validate unit economics: LTV/CAC ratio above 3:1
M|references|- [ ] If not hitting targets, identify whether to pivot or persevere
M|references|| Stage | Primary Metrics | dec Trigger |
M|references||-------|----------------|-----------------|
M|references|| Pre-launch | Landing page conversion, interview quality signals | Below 2% conversion = rethink positioning |
M|references|| Beta | Activation rate, Day-7 retention, feature usage | Below 30% activation = fix onboarding |
M|references|| Early growth | MRR, churn rate, NPS | Above 10% monthly churn = fix value delivery |
M|references|| Scale | LTV/CAC, net revenue retention, payback period | LTV/CAC below 3 = fix economics before scaling |
M|references|Large organizations face unique challenges when applying lean methods: bureaucracy, risk aversion, competing priorities, and the temptation to apply existing processes to fundamentally uncertain work.
M|references|Create a protected environment where lean methods can operate without being crushed by corporate antibodies.
M|references|**Sandbox rules:**
M|references|1. Dedicated team (3-7 people), not part-time contributors
M|references|2. Separate budget with metered funding tied to learning milestones
M|references|3. Authority to experiment with real customers (within defined guardrails)
M|references|4. Reports to a single executive sponsor, not a committee
M|references|5. Immune from normal planning cycles, quarterly reviews, and ap chains for small expenditures
M|references|| Corporate Constraint | Lean Adaptation |
M|references||---------------------|----------------|
M|references|| Brand risk | Use a separate brand or "labs" label for experiments |
M|references|| Legal/compliance rv | Pre-ap experiment templates; legal reviews for categories, not individual experiments |
M|references|| IT infrastructure requirements | Use external cloud services; sandbox data separately from prd |
M|references|| Budget ap cycles | Secure a quarterly innovation budget; spend authority within that budget is delegated to the team |
M|references|| Stakeholder management | Monthly innovation reviews with standardized reporting (not ad-hoc presentations) |
M|references|| Existing customer relationships | Test with non-strategic accounts first; get explicit opt-in for experimental features |
M|references|| Anti-Pattern | Why It Kills Innovation | Fix |
M|references||-------------|------------------------|-----|
M|references|| Innovation theater | Lots of activity, no validated learning | Require experiment results, not activity reports |
M|references|| Success metrics tied to revenue too early | Forces premature scaling of unvalidated ideas | Use innovation accounting metrics for the first 6-12 months |
M|references|| "Not invented here" syndrome | Team dismisses external signals and customer feedback | Mandate customer interviews and competitive analysis |
M|references|| Pilot-to-product gap | Successful pilots die because no path to integration exists | Define the integration path before starting the pilot |
M|references|| Consensus-driven decisions | Every stakeholder must agree before testing | Designate a single dec maker for the innovation team |
M|references|Lean methods apply not just to new products but to individual features within existing products. Every new feature is a hypothesis about what customers want.
M|references|**Step 1: State the hypothesis**
M|references|"We believe that [feature] will cause [metric] to improve by [amount] for [user segment] because [reason]."
M|references|**Step 2: Design the smallest test**
M|references|| Test Type | When to Use | Build Time |
M|references||-----------|-------------|------------|
M|references|| Fake door test | Gauge demand before building | 1 day |
M|references|| Wizard of Oz | Test the experience before building the engine | 3-5 days |
M|references|| Limited rollout | Test with a small percentage of users | 1-2 weeks |
M|references|| A/B test | Compare new feature against current experience | 1-3 weeks |
M|references|| Time-limited pilot | Test with a specific segment for a fixed period | 2-4 weeks |
M|references|**Step 3: Set success criteria before launch**
M|references|**Step 4: Measure and decide**
M|references|- Feature meets criteria: roll out to all users
M|references|- Feature partially meets criteria: iterate and retest
M|references|- Feature misses criteria: kill it and move on
M|references|Define conditions under which a feature should be removed, not just paused:
M|references|- [ ] Adoption below X% after Y weeks of availability
M|references|- [ ] No measurable impact on target metric after full rollout
M|references|- [ ] Increases support tickets without corresponding engagement increase
M|references|- [ ] Negative impact on core metrics (retention, activation, revenue)
M|references|- [ ] Maintenance cost exceeds value delivered
M|references|Most teams add features but never remove them. This creates bloat. Lean teams treat features as experiments that must earn their place.
M|references|Hardware presents unique challenges: longer build cycles, higher iteration costs, and physical supply chain constraints. But lean principles still apply.
M|references|| Lean Principle | Software Implementation | Hardware Adaptation |
M|references||---------------|------------------------|---------------------|
M|references|| MVP | Landing page or single-feature app | 3D-printed prototype, video demonstration, Kickstarter cg |
M|references|| Build-Measure-Learn loops | Weekly cycles | Monthly cycles (still faster than traditional 18-month dev) |
M|references|| Continuous dpl | Deploy code multiple times per day | Rapid prototyping with design iterations every 2-4 weeks |
M|references|| Small batches | Single feature releases | Small prd runs (50-100 units) before mass manufacturing |
M|references|| Pivot | Change product direction | Change form factor, target customer, or use case |
M|references|1. **Validate demand before prototyping.** Use video MVPs, landing pages, or crowdfunding to confirm people want the product before spending on tooling.
M|references|2. **Prototype with off-the-shelf components.** Use Arduino, Raspberry Pi, 3D printing, and existing enclosures to test functionality before custom engineering.
M|references|3. **Test with small prd runs.** Manufacture 50-100 units before committing to mass prd. Use these for real-world testing with customers.
M|references|4. **Separate the software from the hardware.** Where possible, make the software updateable even if the hardware is fixed. This enables iteration on the experience without re-manufacturing.
M|references|5. **Design for modularity.** Modular designs allow component-level iteration without redesigning the entire product.
M|references|| Phase | Duration | Activity | Output |
M|references||-------|----------|----------|--------|
M|references|| Demand validation | 2-4 weeks | Landing page, video, pre-orders | Evidence of demand |
M|references|| Functional prototype | 4-8 weeks | Off-the-shelf components, 3D printing | Working prototype for 10-20 users |
M|references|| User testing | 4-8 weeks | Place prototypes with real users | Usage data, feedback, iteration list |
M|references|| Small batch prd | 8-12 weeks | Manufacture 50-100 units | Real-world performance data |
M|references|| Mass prd dec | 1 week | rv all data | Go/no-go on mass prd |
M|references|Services businesses have a unique advantage for lean: the product is delivered by people, making iteration almost instantaneous.
M|references|**Phase 1: Define the Service MVP**
M|references|- Deliver the service to 3-5 clients manually
M|references|- Do not build a platform, booking system, or brand
M|references|- Focus entirely on delivering value and observing the client experience
M|references|**Phase 2: Systematize What Works**
M|references|- Identify the parts of the service that clients value most
M|references|- Create standard operating procedures for high-value activities
M|references|- Eliminate or reduce low-value activities
M|references|- Create templates and checklists
M|references|**Phase 3: Scale Selectively**
M|references|- Hire or contract for the highest-value, most systematized parts
M|references|- Continue delivering high-touch, variable parts manually
M|references|- Only build technology when manual processes become the bottleneck
M|references|| Experiment | Method | What You Learn |
M|references||-----------|--------|----------------|
M|references|| Value-based pricing | Quote different prices to different (similar) clients | Price sensitivity and perceived value ceiling |
M|references|| Tiered packages | Offer basic/standard/premium | Which value components clients prioritize |
M|references|| Retainer vs project | Offer both to similar clients | Client preference for commitment level |
M|references|| Money-back guarantee | Offer a satisfaction guarantee | Confidence in delivery and client risk perception |
M|references|Nonprofits and government agencies face uncertainty just like startups: will this program achieve its intended impact? Lean methods help them test interventions quickly and allocate resources to what 
M|references|| Startup Concept | Nonprofit Translation |
M|references||----------------|----------------------|
M|references|| Customer | Beneficiary (the person served) and donor/funder (the person who pays) |
M|references|| Revenue | Impact metrics (outcomes achieved) and funding secured |
M|references|| Product-market fit | Program-beneficiary fit (the program achieves intended outcomes) |
M|references|| Growth engine | Funding engine (how the organization sustains itself) |
M|references|| Pivot | Program redesign or population change |
M|references|| MVP | Pilot program with 10-20 beneficiaries |
M|references|1. **Define the theory of change.** What specific intervention will cause what specific outcome for what specific population?
M|references|2. **Identify leap-of-faith assumptions.** What must be true for this intervention to work?
M|references|3. **Design a pilot.** Deliver the intervention to a small group. Measure actual outcomes, not just outputs.
M|references|4. **Distinguish outputs from outcomes.**
M|references|- Output: 100 people attended the workshop
M|references|- Outcome: 40 of those people applied the skills within 30 days
M|references|- Impact: 20 of those people saw measurable improvement in the target area
M|references|5. **Iterate based on outcomes.** If outcomes are below targets, redesign the intervention. If outcomes are strong, scale.
M|references|| Traditional Government | Lean Government |
M|references||----------------------|-----------------|
M|references|| Multi-year planning process | 90-day experiment cycles |
M|references|| Large-scale program launch | Small pilot with 100-500 participants |
M|references|| Measure compliance and outputs | Measure outcomes and beneficiary experience |
M|references|| Evaluation after 3-5 years | Evaluation after each 90-day cycle |
M|references|| Fixed program design | Iterative program design based on data |
M|references|1. **Start with the customer.** Understand the problem before designing the solution.
M|references|2. **Test assumptions, not ideas.** Identify what must be true and validate it.
M|references|3. **Minimize time to learn.** Speed through the learning loop is the fundamental advantage.
M|references|4. **Use actionable metrics.** Measure what informs decisions, not what feels good.
M|references|5. **Make pivot decisions based on evidence.** Not politics, not sunk costs, not ego.
M|references|| ctx Variable | Adaptation |
M|references||-----------------|------------|
M|references|| High regulation (healthcare, fin) | Pre-ap experiment categories with legal/compliance; longer cycles but still experimental |
M|references|| Long sales cycles (enterprise B2B) | Use letters of intent and paid pilots as validation signals; monthly instead of weekly loops |
M|references|| Physical products (hardware, CPG) | Front-load demand validation; use rapid prototyping for solution validation |
M|references|| Two-sided markets (marketplaces) | Validate each side separately; often need concierge for supply side first |
M|references|| Network-dependent products (soc) | Test with small, dense communities; do not try to create a network at scale from day one |
M|references|| High-stakes decisions (medical, legal) | Use simulation and role-playing before real-world testing; involve domain experts in experiment design |
M|references|| Low-tech audiences | Use offline validation methods: paper prototypes, in-person observations, phone surveys |
M|references|The fundamental question is always the same: what is the fastest, cheapest way to learn whether this assumption is true? The answer changes by ctx. The question does not.